05:58.287 --> 06:00.109
Which brings us up to a total of eight. Right, and 
there it is, Detroit 8 airplane. On March 1942,

06:03.592 --> 06:07.636
before the strafing attack on Chiang Mai. Now this 
is after we had evacuated from Rangoon. So you

06:13.002 --> 06:14.964
left, when did you leave Rangoon? Right after the 
26th of February? Did I say 27th? 27th. At 27th. You

06:22.571 --> 06:23.552
left Rangoon. On the 27th, and landed and operated 
out of Magwe, M-A-G-W-E, Burma, on the 28th of

06:23.752 --> 06:30.819
February. Okay,

06:31.900 --> 06:39.428
so you went up to Burma, and how are the conditions 
there? This is where you begin to see the usual

06:40.569 --> 06:49.759
pandemonium and mix-up of war front, 
particularly when you're losing and retreating.

06:55.960 --> 07:06.971
The Japanese were pushing up from Singapore, up 
the peninsula, come across into Rangoon, Burma,

06:55.960 --> 07:06.971
and taking over that base, and they were pushing up 
north towards China. And see, we were evacuating

07:07.491 --> 07:12.316
north up to Irrawaddy River.

07:13.797 --> 07:15.599
That's Mogwe right there. Here is Rangoon, Mogwe. 
No, wait a minute. No, it's up here. Right up here.

07:23.748 --> 07:23.888
OK. This is Mogli right here. That's Tangu.

07:33.240 --> 07:33.681
OK. But it's right in this area. Yeah. OK. How did 
you get them? Could you describe the conditions of

07:40.349 --> 07:43.273
Mogli? The remnants of the RAF air base. and

07:48.667 --> 07:57.739
strictly RAF, the remnants of what had escaped 
from Singapore. And they had a shambles of a light

07:58.941 --> 08:10.256
bomber Blenheim outfit remaining, five or six 
airplanes. They had a couple of old Lysander

08:12.865 --> 08:20.175
observation airplanes, which were practically 
useless for observation and photo

08:12.865 --> 08:20.175
reconnaissance, if you will. And they had about 
four or five hurricanes. And they were hoping for

08:23.800 --> 08:29.107
reinforcements immediately from India, you 
know, to come across. And, of course, they were

08:30.148 --> 08:37.338
delighted for us to stay with them because we were, 
you know, still fighting for them. You began to see

08:37.358 --> 08:42.585
refugees, you know, and that's the thing that you 
remember so well. that shows the effects of war on a

08:43.088 --> 08:46.251
countryside. Peasants with what belongings they 
have left and carts drawn by oxen or Indian water

08:47.573 --> 08:55.061
buffalo. Some wealthy people apparently and a 
nice little foreign car, Japanese automobile.

09:03.050 --> 09:05.873
And the city just overflown. We had, the only place 
we had at Montgomery was tents. The British put up

09:11.279 --> 09:16.405
some tents for us, because they didn't have 
anything else. And if I remember correctly, we

09:16.425 --> 09:22.211
had, I think we had about six airplanes. We had to 
leave one airplane at random, we couldn't get out.

09:29.620 --> 09:31.962
And because we had robbed it before to get the 
others out. I think we had about six airplanes. Of

09:36.413 --> 09:39.336
course, six pilots were flying, including me and 
Bob Neal. Incidentally, two of the boys got lost on

09:39.356 --> 09:43.381
the way up because of sandstorms. Again, no 
navigation aid. But fortunately, they found open

09:46.464 --> 09:51.610
field where they could land, and we got those 
airplanes back. So you only left with six, and you

09:52.191 --> 09:55.535
went down there with, what, 12? Well, you know, we 
had airplanes going back and replaced with parts.

09:59.319 --> 10:02.202
We lost training-wise. several airplanes in 
Rangoon. But actual combat, in actual combat, if I

10:05.445 --> 10:14.473
can remember correctly, I think we lost, in actual 
combat, eight pilots. At Rangoon or the whole

10:16.435 --> 10:18.137
time? No, throughout the entire AVG history. Wow. 
And now, we lost more airplanes than that because,

10:20.899 --> 10:27.304
see, the pilots bailed out. I bailed out of an 
airplane once, see, and I'm still there. So we lost

10:30.567 --> 10:32.509
more airplanes than that. We eventually got our 
100 airplane, just about the time I left 42, and I

10:32.962 --> 10:41.233
helped ferry some of them, the P-40E. But let's get 
back to the conditions now. The people were

10:44.137 --> 10:54.131
crowding into the cities, and how about you slept 
in tents, and that was it. How about the bugs? I

10:57.456 --> 11:00.279
never remember any bad bugs until China. About a 
quarter of them were in China. We really got in a

11:02.695 --> 11:04.076
mess of those. Mosquitoes? I don't remember 
mosquitoes bothering us. I remember at Mogwe, the

11:08.280 --> 11:11.963
tents weren't too bad. It was cool. Hot in the day, 
so you want to be cool at night. I don't ever

11:17.148 --> 11:20.051
remember mosquitoes bothering us anyplace. Were 
you on the floor or on the couch? No, we were in the

11:22.633 --> 11:23.374
couch. And we had mosquito nets, too. In fact, one 
of the main things in Burma was mosquito nets.

11:29.139 --> 11:32.162
Never anything bothered me except some ants got on 
me one time. I think it was because I had some sweets

11:32.328 --> 11:38.717
nutting hair oil on my hair. I woke up with them all 
over my head.

11:43.604 --> 11:46.248
Bed bugs, definitely in Ling Ling, China. A gift 
store came home in August. I was practically eaten

11:48.591 --> 11:50.113
alive with those. Plus bed, I was fed some tongue 
oil, you know, tongue nut. You make paint oil out of

11:56.803 --> 11:59.787
it, mixed with paint. I'm getting ahead of myself, 
but the Chinese went down and bought that instead

12:00.357 --> 12:05.722
of cooking oil to cook their fish in. And the whole 
outfit got sick, including Johnny Allison, who

12:05.742 --> 12:12.229
we're just going to continue doing. At Ma Gui, we 
ate at the British Mess, and this was getting

12:12.489 --> 12:16.713
pretty sparse then. I remember having beer and 
toast for breakfast several times. That's all.

12:21.518 --> 12:22.479
Beer and toast? Hot beer and toast. Why hot beer? 
Well, that was all I had. Didn't have any ice. I

12:29.095 --> 12:35.062
don't remember any decent coffee at all in Burma. 
In China, we got some better coffee, but I didn't

12:35.542 --> 12:40.648
get good coffee until I came back to India. Who was 
supplying you? RAF at that time. The RAF was

12:43.872 --> 12:46.675
supplying you. Was Chenault with you? No, 
Chenault was still up in China. We were

12:51.607 --> 12:56.795
communicating with him through British 
communications, RAF. They kept a link with him,

12:56.815 --> 12:59.119
actually. And radio teletype. How many squadrons 
did he have? He still had three. We always had

13:04.868 --> 13:05.889
three. I know you always had three, but how many 
were with him in China? Two. Two, and you were down

13:11.578 --> 13:13.441
there on your own. He had the what? We weren't 
engaged in any fighting in China at the time

13:16.463 --> 13:21.729
because of the Burma campaign. And he was using the 
reserve forces up at Kunming to rotate and see the

13:21.989 --> 13:27.295
squadron. We were the last squadron to go down to 
Kunming. And I think it, I mean, Rangoon. And I

13:34.404 --> 13:41.712
think even while we were there, he even rotated a 
few aircraft, took some of our bummers and sent

13:34.404 --> 13:41.712
some better ones. maintained one to us without 
rotating another squadron down he kept us there

13:41.995 --> 14:09.927
towards the end it mocked we finally he pulled all 
of us out and replaced us with about six more

13:41.995 --> 14:09.927
college and matter of fact he brought a whole 
squadron down at that time this will be

13:41.995 --> 14:09.927
interesting to you uh general

13:41.995 --> 14:09.927
the old ground pounder And General Fennel got in a 
horrible argument that went clear to the top

14:11.577 --> 14:28.092
between President Roosevelt and General 
Esselstyn about ground support for General

14:11.577 --> 14:28.092
Stillwell's troops.

14:30.654 --> 14:33.957
I had met General Stillwell once or twice. I 
actually sat under a wing of an airplane and talked

14:34.057 --> 14:36.820
with him. He was quite a dedicated old man. ground 
pounder type, if you will. Real dedicated old

14:43.403 --> 14:44.885
gentleman. He looked more like a, you pardon it, a 
college professor in English rather than a

14:45.205 --> 14:53.693
military. I'm glad I wasn't interested. No, I 
mean, he looked to be, John Stilwell, he looked to

14:57.117 --> 15:01.721
be then about 65. No kidding, yeah. He was lean and 
wore some old steel rim spectacles and had a burr

15:03.643 --> 15:10.930
cut haircut. skinny old skinny as a rail and wore 
typical ground pounder old uniform rag taggle

15:11.399 --> 15:41.170
type but more dedicated to his task and he was be 
damned that Burma if the Japs were going to run him

15:11.399 --> 15:41.170
out of Burma he would be damned if they did and he was 
trying to get all of our measly three squadrons if

15:11.399 --> 15:41.170
you will Chinese Air Force dedicated to nothing 
more of a ground support of him if his troops in the

15:41.335 --> 15:43.037
jungle. And of course, we weren't about to do that. 
Why not? Well, General Chenault knew better, and

15:48.064 --> 16:02.743
when it began to trickle down to the pilots that 
General Chenault might be losing this battle and

15:48.064 --> 16:02.743
we'd have to do it, this is one time that morale of 
the flying target began to get pretty low. You

16:04.685 --> 16:07.228
couldn't, you just can't visualize until you see 
it. Trying to support Well, it's sort of like the

16:09.567 --> 16:21.642
Vietnamese War, trying to support some, if you 
will, jungle fighters in the jungles that are so

16:09.567 --> 16:21.642
thick with trees that range anywhere from 100 feet 
to 200 feet high. No way to see them. Plus the fact

16:23.244 --> 16:32.895
that operate that low with a P-40 and no way to dive 
away should the Zeros come in and get on top of you,

16:23.244 --> 16:32.895
you're a dead duck. And we knew it. And boy, we 
just... One squadron was ready to... Throwing a

16:38.592 --> 16:43.837
towel had the Generalissimo, I had General 
Chennault do it. Had Stillwell. Had his way. So

16:47.119 --> 16:49.361
Chennault and Stillwell were arguing about this. 
Oh, violent enemies. They were worse than General

16:50.903 --> 16:55.066
Chennault and General Hepburn. But through

16:55.086 --> 17:07.097
the Gissimo, Generalissimo, General Chennault 
won his argument and said, no, first priority is

16:55.086 --> 17:07.097
still the air defense. And so none of us had to do. 
There were two or three missions flown on this, and

17:10.966 --> 17:15.911
boy, the pilots, they didn't like it at all. I never 
went on a mission like that, but I wouldn't have

17:16.331 --> 17:20.015
liked it either. How could you help them? I mean, 
how could you give them any support if you couldn't

17:22.077 --> 17:24.359
find them? That's it. It was worthless. It was 
absolutely worthless. Useless. And it was almost

17:28.143 --> 17:32.126
a suicide flight should a Japanese come over the 
interception. And what did you think of Stilwell?

17:35.069 --> 17:36.190
Well, that's the reason I didn't like him. Because 
he was being unreasonable. He was one of the older

17:39.383 --> 17:45.911
types, and I really don't think he understood air 
power. Plus the fact that at

17:45.931 --> 17:59.287
that time, just at the starting of the war, air 
power hadn't really made itself known. And

17:59.567 --> 18:06.295
I don't think he understood it at all.

18:07.608 --> 18:14.737
We would have done it had we been ordered to do it, 
but General Chenault, I'm sure, would have been

18:07.608 --> 18:14.737
the last man to agree with it. Now, when you were, 
you said before that you were sitting underneath

18:14.758 --> 18:19.544
an airplane with Stilwell. Tell me about that. I 
just had, he was waiting for a pilot in nearby

18:20.886 --> 18:26.393
Gutenberg to take him. It was one of these things, 
he'd been down to talk to Schmeltz, he'd been back

18:26.744 --> 18:35.697
at Chung King, and during his time he was talking 
about this fight that was going on. At that

18:35.997 --> 18:40.544
particular time I was sitting with him, I didn't 
know all this background. This was the early days

18:40.564 --> 18:43.067
of it. Like I told you, I gave my impression of him as 
an elderly old boy. He talked to me. Never asked me

18:52.445 --> 18:57.512
many questions about my combat experience or how 
you're doing or anything. I guess he was

18:57.813 --> 19:00.576
preoccupied with thought. I didn't, at that time, 
I'm not sure I realized really how big a man he was.

19:08.267 --> 19:21.726
But later on, later on, you know, knowing what I, 
learning what I did, that's

19:08.267 --> 19:21.726
the reason I have no respect for him. As a military, 
as an army commander, I'm sure that the old boy was

19:22.246 --> 19:37.242
dedicated, and he had his objective and had his 
job, but he was completely, to do what he wanted to

19:22.246 --> 19:37.242
do was completely unreasonable. No way. And it was 
not enough. Finally what happened was the Chinese

19:41.507 --> 19:49.215
stopped the Japanese at the northern reaches of 
Burma

19:52.790 --> 19:54.672
the Mekong River. The

19:55.573 --> 20:16.051
Chinese

19:55.573 --> 20:16.051
actually stopped them. They never did actually 
penetrate the southern border of China. Then the

20:20.416 --> 20:22.037
Japanese decided to come from the north down too. 
So Stilwell never did reject or eject the Japanese

20:23.689 --> 20:31.078
out of northern Burma. Eventually, they just 
withdrew because of higher priorities in other

20:31.478 --> 20:37.326
areas when they began to lose the war. But at any 
rate, Stilwell lost his battle with the old man,

20:39.709 --> 20:45.836
and we continue to do everything. OK. Now, how long 
were you at? Now, I

20:51.903 --> 21:06.805
and my bunch, the first squadron, we were replaced 
by one of the other squadrons, partially, and

20:51.903 --> 21:06.805
there were only six airplanes. We went on back up to 
Kunming. This was in early February, I believe.

21:13.515 --> 21:16.459
No, early March.

21:18.852 --> 21:34.611
The short after we left Magui, by the way, the base 
was real hard hit by the Japanese, and we lost, one

21:18.852 --> 21:34.611
pilot was killed on the ground, one of our pilots 
was killed on the ground from bombing, and we lost

21:18.852 --> 21:34.611
about two or three aircraft. And the British 
evacuated down, of course, so did we. Then we

21:39.497 --> 21:45.764
backed up clear into lower wing across, right 
across the river into southern China. And in

21:45.784 --> 21:46.665
effect, turn Burma over to the Japanese. Then we 
operated out of lower wing on the same type of

21:50.182 --> 21:52.886
mission. Were you disappointed about losing 
Burma?

