Looking back now, yeah, we were disappointed. It 
looked as though the Japanese were winning the

22:05.645 --> 22:07.989
war.

22:10.673 --> 22:13.056
We were being squeezed back up into China. As a 
matter of fact, at times we'd sit in bull sessions

22:16.936 --> 22:21.965
and figure at the end of our year's contract, say 
September, how in the world would we get out of

22:16.936 --> 22:21.965
China? The Japanese had the coast block, now they 
had the south block of Burma, and we dreamed up ways

22:22.686 --> 22:41.138
to go through the Himalayas some way back down 
through Afghanistan into India. course never

22:41.573 --> 22:43.075
turned out to be that way. Then of course they 
developed the, that's one reason they developed

22:43.095 --> 22:53.888
the hump route with air and even tried to build a 
Lido road across it to get supplies into China. And

22:54.689 --> 22:59.716
that's what generated the Chiang Mai raid. Chiang 
Mai, Thailand. Okay, that was, okay, that was your

23:01.918 --> 23:05.182
next major raid. For our squadron. I mean for you. 
Oh, for me, right. I'm not talking about—I'm

23:10.500 --> 23:14.005
talking about you. See, we drew the two squadrons 
back up into Kunming, and then eventually had to

23:14.105 --> 23:22.338
operate with one of them in Lower Wing, one in Lower 
Wing and two in Kunming. And then, you know, to get

23:22.358 --> 23:26.525
back into war, the old man dreamed up this mission. 
